<p>'So they have to be really mindful, first of all, of the safety of residents, the safety of the visitors and of the staff, and also the potential to make sure that every single aspect of this has been covered so that they might be able to justify that if there is legal action later.'</p>

<p>A DHSC spokesman said: 'We know that limiting visits in care homes has been difficult for many families and residents who want to see their loved ones, but our first priority is to prevent infections in care homes, and this means that visiting policy should still be restricted, with alternatives sought wherever possible.</p>

<p>'Visiting policies should be tailored by the individual care home and taking into account local risks in their area.'</p>
